  "prompt": "Which are the best british fictional books?",
  "response": "The \"best\" British fictional books can be subjective and depend on personal taste, but there are several classic and contemporary works that have been widely acclaimed and are considered essential reading. Here are some of the most celebrated British novels:\n\n1. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen** - A timeless romance and social commentary set in early 19th-century England.\n\n2. **\"1984\" by George Orwell** - A dystopian novel that explores themes of totalitarianism, surveillance, and individuality.\n\n3. **\"To the Lighthouse\" by Virginia Woolf** - A modernist novel that delves into the complexities of family relationships and the passage of time.\n\n4. **\"Great Expectations\" by Charles Dickens** - A bildungsroman that follows the life of Pip, an orphan who dreams of becoming a gentleman.\n\n5. **\"Jane Eyre\" by Charlotte Bront\u00eb** - A novel that combines a passionate love story with a critique of Victorian class and gender roles.\n\n6. **\"Wuthering Heights\" by Emily Bront\u00eb** - A Gothic novel of unchecked passion and revenge set in the wild Yorkshire moors.\n\n7. **\"The Picture of Dorian Gray\" by Oscar Wilde** - A philosophical and aesthetic novel that explores themes of vanity, pleasure, and morality.\n\n8. **\"Mrs Dalloway\" by Virginia Woolf** - Another modernist masterpiece, focusing on a single day in the life of Clarissa Dalloway.\n\n9. **\"Brave New World\" by Aldous Huxley** - A dystopian novel that envisions a future society driven by technological advancements and consumerism.\n\n10. **\"The Remains of the Day\" by Kazuo Ishiguro** - A novel of subtlety and restraint, reflecting on themes of dignity, regret, and the passing of an era.\n\n11. **\"Never Let Me Go\" by Kazuo Ishiguro** - A poignant tale of love and loss, with a science fiction premise that raises ethical questions about cloning and humanity.\n\n12. **\"Atonement\" by Ian McEwan** - A novel that intertwines love and war, and the irreparable consequences of a young girl's mistake.\n\n13. **\"The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy\" by Douglas Adams** - A humorous and whimsical science fiction series that has become a cult classic.\n\n14. **\"Brideshead Revisited\" by Evelyn Waugh** - A nostalgic and evocative novel of a bygone aristocratic England.\n\n15. **\"The Secret History\" by Donna Tartt** - A psychological thriller that delves into the world of a group of classics students at an elite college.\n\nThese books span a range of genres and styles, from the Romantic era to modernist and postmodernist works, and from social realism to science fiction. They offer insights into British culture, history, and human nature, and have influenced countless readers and writers around the world.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
